<div id="comment_64564035" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64564035" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64564035" name="comment_link_64564035" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23363177&amp;cid=64564035" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64564035)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64564035" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64564035); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Aristos+Mazer">Aristos Mazer</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Aristos+Mazer">( 181252 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64564035"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64564035"><p>In this case, it fails due to network effect. The site that can aggregate more information wins over all competitors as customers only use one. In order for another site to compete, all the users who generate content would need to be uploading to all the competitors every time they upload to YouTube. That ain't going to happen. It's not a market failure in the classic sense of having driven out all competitors. Instead, it's a case for making YouTube into a regulated monopoly utility.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64564035">

